The paper proposes a framework for robot localization and mapping in dynamic environments using spatiotemporal articulated models. This falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO) as it involves developing a method for robot localization and mapping. The method also involves computer vision techniques for estimating articulated structure and predicting future motions, which falls under computer vision (cs.CV). The use of machine learning for temporal prediction also suggests the possibility of the paper belonging to the machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI) categories. Finally, the application of the proposed framework to dynamic environments suggests the possibility of the paper belonging to the systems and control (cs.SY) category.
